President Obama addressed the National Council of La Raza (NCLR), the largest national Latino civil rights and advocacy organization in America, at their Annual Conference luncheon in 2011. The President discussed the importance of ensuring equal opportunities for all Americans and highlighted the significance of the growing Hispanic community in America. The address came after the White House hosted a Hispanic Policy Conference, bringing together community leaders and officials to discuss the Administration's efforts related to the Hispanic community. The President's speech was live-streamed, and other Administration officials, including Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack and Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar, also participated in the conference. The article also mentioned the Administration's participation in other Hispanic conferences throughout the summer and the President and Administration officials speaking at commencement ceremonies at Hispanic-Serving Institutions. For more information on these events and the Administration's engagement with the Hispanic community, readers were directed to visit the White House website.